Part 1: warm-up exercise.¶

The function below draws a sample from an unnormalised discrete distribution.

  1. Explain how it works
  2. Write a vectorised version, which takes the number of samples to generate as an extra parameter, and returns a numpy array of samples
In [3]:
def sample_discrete(b):
    r = np.sum(b)*np.random.random();
    a = b[0].copy()
    i = 0
    while a < r:
        i += 1
        a += b[i]
    return i

Here's an example of how it works, with probabilities b

Answer1¶

Conclusion: We can see that the vectorized version of sampler is faster than the other two versions and robust to size of input (doesn't give memory error if hypothetical inputs are of million dimensions)

In [5]:
# A simple extension of function above without vectorization 

def sample_discrete_multi_novec(b,n): # no vectorization
    sample=np.zeros(n)
    for i in range(n):
        r = np.sum(b)*np.random.random()
        a = b[0].copy()
        j = 0
        while a < r:
            j += 1
            a += b[j]
        sample[i]=j  
    return sample
In [6]:
# Vectorized function

def sample_discrete_multi_vectorized(b,n):
    r = np.sum(b)*np.random.random(n).reshape(n,1)
    y = r>np.cumsum(b)
    return y.sum(axis=1)
In [7]:
# A mini-batch style vectorized sampler robust for hypothetically large input sizes

def fast_sampler(b, n, memory_const=2e9):
    # reasonable memory buffer of 2 giga-BITS = 1/4 giga-BYTE 
    
    # preset output, datatype can be an integer
    ret = np.empty((n,), dtype=int)
    # number of classes
    m = b.size
    # calculate maximum number of samples per mini-batch
    # and make sure n is a integer type (otherwise problems may occur in the next step)
    k = int(memory_const//m) if n*m > memory_const else int(n)
    # loop over number of batches
    for i in range(np.ceil(n/k).astype(int)):
        # check if this batch is too large
        ch = (n<(i+1)*k)
        # number of samples taken
        k_acc = (i+1)*k
        # samples to be taken in this step
        k_step = int(k- ch*(k_acc-n))
        # take the next k or the remaining samples respectively
        ret[k*i:k*i + k_step] = sample_discrete_multi_vectorized(b,k_step)
    return ret

Topic Modeling¶

This section is about unsupervised learning with text data. We'll be using a relatively small dataset, consisting of 3430 documents and a vocabulary of 6906 words drawn from the daily kos blog around 2004.

You can download the data here.

Bayesian mixture model¶

We're going to model the documents as bags of words, with a bayesian mixture model. The documents are modeled using $K$ topics. The assignment of a document to a topic is modeled by the latent variable $z_d$.

The topics are drawn from a categorical distribution with parameters $\theta$, where $\theta$ is drawn from a Dirichlet prior with parameter $\alpha$.

Each topic specifies a categorical distribution over words. The prior on each of these distributions is a Dirichlet with parameter $\gamma$.

The figure below shows this in a graphical model.

For simplicity, let's denote with $y_n$ the observations (i.e. the documents we see in the corpus). The conditional likelihood is:

$$p(y_n|z_n \negmedspace = \negmedspace k,\beta) = p(y_n|\beta_k) = p(y_n|\beta_{z_n})$$

And we have a prior:

$$p(\beta_k)$$

And a (latent) categorical assignment probability:

$$p(z_n \negmedspace= \negmedspace k|\theta) = \theta_k$$

which has a Dirichlet prior:

$$p(\theta|\alpha) = Dir(\alpha)$$

Which gives our latent posterior:

$$ p(z_n\negmedspace=\negmedspace k|y_n,\theta,\beta) \quad \propto p(z_n\negmedspace =\negmedspace k|\theta)p(y_n|z_n \negmedspace = \negmedspace k,\beta) \quad \propto \theta_k p(y_n|\beta_{z_n}) $$

Gibbs Sampling¶

We will explore this model by drawing from the posterior using MCMC, specifically Gibbs sampling.

We will alternately sample the three types of variables, & iterate this procedure multiple times.

First we'll sample the component parameters:

$$p(\beta_k|y,z) \quad \propto p(\beta_k) \prod_{n:z_n=k} p(y_n|\beta_k) $$

Then the latent allocations of documents to topics: $$ p(z_n \negmedspace= \negmedspace k|y_n,\theta,\beta) \quad \propto \theta_k p(y_n|\beta_{z_n})$$

and then the mixing proportions:

$$p(\theta|z,\alpha) = p(\theta|\alpha)p(z|\theta) = \mathrm{Dir}\left(\frac{c_k+\alpha_k}{\sum_j c_j + \alpha_j}\right)$$

where $c_k$ are the counts for mixture component $k$.

The Collapsed Gibbs Sampler¶

We marginalise over $\theta$. (You do not need to derive this result). N.B. the notation $c_{-n}$ indicates all indices except $n$.

$$p(z_n \negmedspace= \negmedspace k|z_{-n},\alpha) = \frac{\alpha + c_{-n,k}}{\sum_j \alpha + c_{-n,j}}$$

which gives the collapsed gibbs sampler for the latent assignments:

$$p(z_n \negmedspace= \negmedspace k|y_n,z_{-n},\beta,\alpha) \propto p(y_n|\beta_k) \frac{\alpha + c_{-n,k}}{\sum_j \alpha + c_{-n,j}}$$

Code¶

The documents have been split into two corpora, A and B.

The array words is a list of all the words in both corpora. The matrices A and B are the train and test corpora, respectively. Each has 3 columns, there is one row for each unique word in each document.

The first column is the document index, second is the word index (corresponding to words), and the third is the number of times that word appears in the document.

In [4]:
# Load datasets and get few dimensions 

A = np.load('mat_A.npy')
B = np.load('mat_B.npy')
words = np.load('words.npy')

W = np.max(np.hstack((A[:,1],B[:,1]))) + 1   # number of unique words
D = np.max(A[:,0]) + 1   # number of documents in A
K = 20 # number of mixture components we will use
N = np.sum(A[:,2]) # total number of words in A with repetition 
alpha = 10  # parameter of the Dirichlet over mixture components
gamma = 0.1 # parameter of the Dirichlet over words

The function below defines the following matrices:

  • sd : the mixture component assignment of each document
  • swk : K multinomial distributions over W unique words
  • sk_docs : the number of documents assigned to each mixture component
  • sk_words : the number of words assigned to mix component k accross all docs

These are initialised by assigning each document to a mixture component at random.

In [15]:
def init():
    sd = np.floor(K*np.random.random((D,1))).astype(int)   
    swk = np.zeros((W,K))              
    sk_docs = np.zeros((K,1)) 

    for d in np.arange(D): 
        w = A[A[:,0]==d,1]      # unique words in doc d
        c = A[A[:,0]==d,2]      # counts
        k = sd[d]               # doc d is in mixture k
        swk[w,k] = swk[w,k] + c # num times word w is assigned to mixture component k
        sk_docs[k] = sk_docs[k] + 1

    sk_words = np.sum(swk,axis=0).T
    return sd, swk, sk_docs, sk_words

The following code starts from this initial state & then performs a number of gibbs sampling sweeps. We will use the collapsed Gibbs sampler, which uses the trick of excluding the current document's counts before calculating the posterior and resampling.

In [121]:
sd, swk, sk_docs, sk_words = init()
num_sweeps = 100
perplexity_iters=np.zeros(num_sweeps)
# This makes a number of Gibbs sampling sweeps through all docs and words
for i_sweep in np.arange(num_sweeps): 
    print("gibbs sweep : {0}".format(i_sweep))
    for d in np.arange(D):
        w = A[A[:,0]==d,1]      # unique words in doc d
        c = A[A[:,0]==d,2]      # counts

        # remove doc d's contributions from count tables
        swk[w,sd[d]] = swk[w,sd[d]] - c 
        sk_docs[sd[d]] = sk_docs[sd[d]] - 1 
        sk_words[sd[d]] = sk_words[sd[d]] - np.sum(c) 
        
        # log probability of doc d under each mixture component
        lb = np.zeros(K)    
        for k in np.arange(K):
            ll = np.dot(c,( np.log(swk[w,k]+gamma) - np.log(sk_words[k] + gamma*W) ))
            lb[k] = np.log(sk_docs[k] + alpha) + ll

        # assign doc d to a new component
        b = np.exp(lb-np.max(lb))  
        kk = sample_discrete(b)  

        # add back doc d's contributions from count tables
        swk[w,kk] = swk[w,kk] + c 
        sk_docs[kk] = sk_docs[kk] + 1 
        sk_words[kk] = sk_words[kk] + np.sum(c)
        sd[d] = kk
        
    # per word-perplexity of the test corpus B per every gibbs sweep
    lp = 0; nd = 0
    doc_B = np.unique(B[:,0])
    for d in range(2000,2000+len(doc_B)):
        w = B[B[:,0]==d,1]    #unique words in doc d
        c = B[B[:,0]==d,2]    # counts
        u = np.log(sk_docs[:] + alpha) - np.log(np.sum(sk_docs[:])+alpha)
        for k in range(K):
            b = (swk[:,k]+gamma)/(sk_words[k] + gamma*W)
            u[k] = u[k] + np.dot(c,np.log(b[w]))
        lp = lp + np.log(np.sum(np.exp(u-np.max(u))))+ np.max(u)
        nd = nd + np.sum(c)  # number of words, doc d

    perplexity_iters[i_sweep] = np.exp(-lp/nd) # perplexity

Part 2:¶

  1. Explain what the code above does. Are you happy with this model? What are its deficiencies?
  2. Calculate the log probability of the first document in corpus B. What does this number mean?
  3. Calculate the per-word perplexity of the test corpus. What does this number mean? Is it good?

Answers:

1ans. The code above is a variant of Topic modeling task, where a collections of documents are modeled into various topics. It is a bayesian mixture model where observations are entire documents with collapsed gibbs sampling, a randomized statistical inference algorithm. It models each document (2000 of them) as a single topic (20 of them).

I am not happy with the default model. It had to be run for more iterations (default 10) to reduce perplexity of test corpus B as seen from figure above. Also, to check robustness of the above model, it needs to be run for different topic(K) values and perplexity on training and test tests needs to compared (choose the one with lower perplexity). In addition the hyperparamters alpha and gamma could be tuned using a grid search and perplexity as evaluation metric

This bayesian mixture model doesn't capture the phenomenon of a mixed membership model like LDA, where a document is associated with a collection of topics. This model may not be good for generalization on new unseen data.

2ans. The log probablitiy of the first document in corpus B is -3620.015. The goodness-of-fit of a model is evaluated using log probablity of held-out or test documents that are not used for training. (another way to do it is using perplexity)

3ans. In text modeling, per word perplexity is a measure of the performance. Lower value of perplexity indicate lower misrepresentaion of words of the test documentss by trained topics. The per-word perplixity of the test corpus B is 2122.42. For common words the perplexity would be small and for rear words high. This is reason different documents have different perplexity values.

Modeling using LDA model from gensim¶

Perplexity:  -7.87172745230938

Coherence Score:  0.27715338349244445

Interpretation:

  1. Larger the bubble more prevalent the topic.
  2. A good model is representative of fairly big non-overlapping bubbles scattered (instead of being in one quadrant)
  3. If model is asked to give out too many topics, it will have many overlaps and clustering of topics in a quadrant.

Scope: The optimal number of topics could be dervied by plotting coherance score vs number of topics or by using a heirarchical dirichlet process

https://datascience.stackexchange.com/questions/128/latent-dirichlet-allocation-vs-hierarchical-dirichlet-process

Conclusion: We can observe that the gensim LDA is not good in comparision to the mallet LDA (see below) as the latter has topics scattered with relatively less overlapping

def format_topics_sentences(ldamodel=lda_model, corpus=corpus, texts=text_all):
    # Init output
    sent_topics_df = pd.DataFrame()

    # Get main topic in each document
    for i, row in enumerate(ldamodel[corpus]):
        row = sorted(row[0], key=lambda x: (x[1]), reverse=True)
        # Get the Dominant topic, Perc Contribution and Keywords for each document
        for j, (topic_num, prop_topic) in enumerate(row):
            if j == 0:  # => dominant topic
                wp = ldamodel.show_topic(topic_num)
                topic_keywords = ", ".join([word for word, prop in wp])
                sent_topics_df = sent_topics_df.append(pd.Series([int(topic_num), round(prop_topic,4), topic_keywords]), ignore_index=True)
            else:
                break
    sent_topics_df.columns = ['Dominant_Topic', 'Perc_Contribution', 'Topic_Keywords']

    # Add original text to the end of the output
    contents = pd.Series(texts)
    sent_topics_df = pd.concat([sent_topics_df, contents], axis=1)
    return(sent_topics_df)


df_topic_sents_keywords = format_topics_sentences(ldamodel=lda_model, corpus=corpus, texts=text_all)
